\begin_layout Standard
We calibrate our estimate of biomass at the time of settlement because we
 have more robust estimates of forest biomass at this time than at modern
 time, forests at this time were much less affected by massive human land
 use change, and these forests are more representative of forests in the
 deep past than modern forests 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "goring2015changes"

\end_inset

.
 This is similar to the approach used by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dawson2016quantifying"

\end_inset

.
 We used the calibration dataset from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dawson2016quantifying"

\end_inset

 with additional calibration points from cores added to Neotoma since 2016,
 giving us a total of 232 calibration points across the Upper Midwest.
 The choice of which pollen sample at each site would be part of the calibration
 dataset was determined using expert elicitation.
 We chose pollen samples to be used for calibration from just before the
 time of settlement using expert elicitation to determine the settlement
 horizon in each pollen core record.
 These methods are covered more extensively in Dawson 2016.
 Basically, each pollen core diagram was sent to expert paleo-ecologists
 who were surveyed about when settlement began to occur on the landscape
 according to the pollen diagram.
 Paleo-ecologists determine the settlement horizon by looking at pollen
 abundances and typically select a settlement horizon when more grass type
 pollen enters the pollen diagram, indicative of land use change that is
 a symptom of settlement.
 Palynologist experts (Jackson and Williams
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Jason has not yet completed the EE
\end_layout

\end_inset

) selected the depth in each core immediately preceding an increase herbaceous
 species, which indicates an increase in agricultural activities representing
 the settlement horizon.
 Each site's samples were organized by sample age.
 Sites were excluded if any expert could not select a settlement horizon
 sample or if experts disagreed about the location of the settlement horizon
 sample within plus or minus two samples.
 
\end_layout

