The calibration model estimates coefficients of spline basis functions that
 nonlinearly relate pollen taxa vectors to biomass point estimates.
 Once calibrated, we fit a prediction model that uses the coefficients estimated
 in the calibration model, pollen count data available at multiple times,
 and a model structure that ensures that biomass varies smoothly over time
 to make biomass point predictions at individual sites.
 These predictions are made every 100 years from the time of settlement
 (100 years before present) to 10,000 years before present.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we use an inverse modeling approach that models pollen counts
 as a function of biomass rather than a regression modeling approach that
 models biomass as a function of pollen counts (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "blarquez2015tree,seppa2009calibrated"

\end_inset

 for examples of the regression approach).
 The inverse modeling approach allows us to build a statistical model for
 changes in biomass over time that enforces smoothness in the biomass process
 through a prior distribution on biomass as a latent (i.e., unobserved) temporal
 process.
 This allows us to combine information from the pollen data while enforcing
 realistic changes over time.
 In contrast a regression modeling approach would not be able to enforce
 smoothness over time; jumps in pollen composition would translate directly
 into (unrealistic) jumps in biomass.
 Also note that we do not explicitly model pollen dispersal, which allows
 us to avoid having to specify a statistical model for the unknown species
 composition across the landscape.
 These choices allow us to keep the model relatively simple and relate directly
 the univariate variable of interest (total biomass) to the multivariate
 dependent variable (pollen composition).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our two step approach also allows us to have greater flexibility in model
 development and assessment.
 Alternatively, we could have fit the calibration and prediction models
 in a comprehensive framework, but we separate them to be able to develop
 alternative calibration models and fit prediction models one site at a
 time.
 Neither model includes spatial uncertainty, which preserves model simplicity
 and computational efficiency, leaving spatial-temporal modeling of all
 the sites jointly for future work.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dawson2016quantifying"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "paciorek2009mapping"

\end_inset

 for similar strategies.
\end_layout

