\begin_layout Subsection
Overall Biomass Prediction Metric Calculation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We computed two metrics to assess overall, region-wide biomass change across
 sites for the last 10,000 years from the MCMC output of the prediction
 model applied to each site.
 First, we calculated median biomass across sites by calculating the median
 biomass (across MCMC samples) at each time step at each site then calculating
 the quantiles of the medians (across sites) at each time step.
 Second, we calculated the probability of biomass increase across sites
 by calculating the difference between biomass estimates for each MCMC iteration
 at each site and each time step.
 From this difference matrix, we calculate the 95% quantiles.
 We chose to include estimates at sites from before and after the first
 and last samples available for the site in order to maintain consistency
 throughout our time series estimates, thus estimating 10,000 years of biomass
 for each site no matter when the first and last sample date is.
 This is reflected in the uncertainty of each time series estimate where
 the uncertainty grows with distance from the nearest data point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All model results were calculated in the R 3.5.1 computing environment using
 Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods.
 The calibration and prediction models were fit using the NIMBLE modeling
 platform (R package version 0.6-12), which allows for significantly increased
 computational efficiency (via a customized MCMC sampling algorithm) and
 model specification flexibility 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de2017programming"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
MCMC algorithms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For both the calibration and prediction models, we analytically marginalized
 (integrated) over the unknown 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

's thereby reducing parameter dimensionality and improving MCMC performance.
 The calibration model was fit using NIMBLE's default adaptive Metropolis
 random walk MCMC samplers for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, achieving good MCMC performance for the prediction model required
 additional work.
 We initially attempted to fit the prediction model above using the default
 MCMC sampling strategy in NIMBLE as well as the default HMC sampler in
 Stan (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "CarpenterBob2017S:AP"

\end_inset

).
 In the former case, we found that the strong (and complicated structure
 of the) posterior correlation between biomass values at nearby points in
 time caused very poor mixing.
 In contrast, in Stan, the biomass values appeared to mix well, but chains
 started at different starting points revealed that the sampler was getting
 stuck in local modes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To address the mixing issues, we used NIMBLE's flexibility in adding custom
 samplers to define a specialized sampler that proposed carefully-tailored
 proposals for biomass values within small time windows.
 In particular we want to propose new biomass values that produce a full
 biomass process that is consistent with the GP structure and that allows
 for large enough moves in the space of the biomass process.
 This is not readily done with the form of the generalized Pareto given
 above because of the complicated and strong dependence structure of the
 biomass values caused by the higher-order temporal structure and generalized
 Pareto distribution.
 However one can use a data augmentation scheme to write the generalized
 Pareto distribution in terms of normal distributions for the biomass contrasts.
 We then also developed a normal approximation to the likelihood.
 Combined these two pieces allow us to propose (using the conditional distributi
on of biomass given the approximate likelihood) biomass process values consisten
t with the data and the GP prior structure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More specifically, first consider the likelihood approximation.
 Having integrated over the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

's in (Eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pred likelihood"

\end_inset

) we can numerically maximize over 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t[i]}$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}_{i}$
\end_inset

 , producing 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{t[i]}$
\end_inset

 and a standard error estimate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{se}(b_{t[i]})$
\end_inset

, based on the second derivative of the likelihood.
 This defines a normal approximation to the likelihood
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{b}_{t[i]}\sim N(b_{t[i]},\hat{se}(b_{t[i]})^{2}).
\]

\end_inset

Next note that following [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "taddy2013multinomial,armagan2013generalized,tansey2017multiscale"

\end_inset

] the generalized Pareto can be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
b_{t} & \sim & N(3b_{t-1}-3b_{t-2}+3b_{t-3},\omega_{t})\label{eq:expanded1}\\
\omega_{t} & \sim & \mathrm{Expon}\left(\lambda_{t}\left(\frac{\lambda_{t}}{2}\right)\right)\label{eq:expanded2}\\
\lambda_{t} & \sim & \mathrm{gamma}(1,\sigma)\label{eq:expanded3}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the same parameter as in the (marginalized) model (Eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GP"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a default MCMC fit to the augmented model, there is high correlation
 between 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\omega_{t},\lambda_{t}\}$
\end_inset

 and values of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 for times near to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, so we can't simply use the conjugate normal structure to sample 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 separately from the variance components.
 Also note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{t}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

 are strongly negatively correlated.
 Given these facts we developed the following joint proposal for 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\omega_{t},\lambda_{t},\boldsymbol{b}_{t,l}\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{t,l}=b_{t-l},\ldots,b_{t-1},b_{t},b_{t+1},\ldots,b_{t+l}$
\end_inset

 are the biomass values within a time window defined by lag 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Propose 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\log\omega_{t}^{*},\log\lambda_{t}^{*}\}$
\end_inset

 from a bivariate normal distribution with negative correlation, centered
 on the current values
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\log\omega_{t}^{*},\log\lambda_{t}^{*}\}$
\end_inset

, propose 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{t,l}^{*}|\log\omega_{t}^{*},\boldsymbol{b}_{t,\backslash l},\hat{\boldsymbol{y}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{t,\backslash l}=b_{1},\ldots,b_{t-l-1},b_{t+l+1},\ldots,b_{T}$
\end_inset

 are the biomass values outside the time window and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{y}}=\{\hat{b}_{1},\hat{b}_{2},\ldots,\hat{b}_{n_{j}},\hat{se}(b_{1}),\hat{se}(b_{2}),\ldots,\hat{se}(b_{n_{j}})\}$
\end_inset

 represents the full set of pseudo-observations and pseudo-standard errors
 from the normal approximation to the likelihood.
 The proposal is the conditional normal distribution for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{t,l}$
\end_inset

 given the likelihood approximation, which can be derived in closed form
 using standard Bayesian multivariate normal calculations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given that the sampler above is a Metropolis-Hastings proposal in step 1
 combined with a sample from an approximation to the true conditional distributi
on for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{t,l}$
\end_inset

 we jointly accept or reject 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\log\omega_{t}^{*},\log\lambda_{t}^{*},\boldsymbol{b}_{t,l}^{*}\}$
\end_inset

 based on standard Metropolis-Hastings calculations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively we are proposing to shift the biomass values in a small time
 window given the new values of the variance parameters but in such a way
 that the proposed biomass values are consistent with the biomass outside
 the time window (in particular the transition from inside to outside the
 window is consistent with the GP prior structure, which can impose very
 tight constraints given the spike at zero) and with the data.
 We choose to propose biomass only within a window to avoid relying too
 heavily on the likelihood approximation and to avoid needing to have good
 proposals for the entire biomass process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our MCMC sampling scheme consists of the sampler above applied at all time
 points, as well as simple Metropolis random walk samplers for 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 for all time points and simple Metropolis random walk samplers for 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

 for all time points.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that in work we found after implementing our approach, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "FaulknerMirin2018"

\end_inset

 report that using HMC in Stan on the expanded model (Eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:expanded1"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:expanded3"

\end_inset

) as opposed to the marginalized model (Eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GP"

\end_inset

) worked well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
