name "subsec:Uncertainty-propagation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We propagated uncertainty from the biomass data product at time of settlement
 (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Vegetation-data"

\end_inset

) into the calibration model and the ages of the pollen samples and the
 beta coefficients estimated in the calibration model into the prediction
 model.
 Uncertainty from the biomass at time of settlement was propagated through
 by fitting the calibration model 50 times, each with a draw from the posterior
 samples of the biomass data product.
 The final MCMC iteration from each of the 50 calibration model fits was
 used in a separate MCMC for the prediction model, where each MCMC also
 used a separate draw from the BACON age depth model MCMC samples.
 This allowed us to propagate uncertainty from the biomass estimate at time
 of settlement, the ages of the pollen samples, and the estimated beta coefficie
nts into our final estimates of biomass at each prediction site.
 Fitting the prediction model multiple times for different biomass estimates,
 dating estimates, and beta spline coefficients has the added benefit of
 allowing us to average over multiple modes that are the result of bimodality
 issues in the prediction model posterior distributions which are further
 discussed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Instability-and-Outliers"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

