\begin_layout Section
Instability and Outliers in Model Predictions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Instability-and-Outliers"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assessed our predictions for instability caused by bimodal likelihoods
 as well as for outliers identified in validation to identify where our
 model does not fit well.
 While assessing the calibration and prediction models we found that the
 likelihood functions (as functions of unknown biomass in the prediction
 model and held-out biomass in the calibration model) were bimodal, indicating
 the models had difficulty in distinguishing low versus high biomass based
 on some pollen samples.
 At some sites, this led to under prediction of biomass particularly during
 the 10-fold cross validation where the high biomass sites were left out
 of calibration (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:10-fold-final"

\end_inset

).
 Perhaps unsurprisingly, we also found in our calibration model that different
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 coefficient estimates led to different maximum likelihood estimates of
 biomass.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2/3 liks"

\end_inset

, we show the likelihood plots for settlement biomass estimated using two
 different sets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 estimates.
 This bimodality can lead to instability in our biomass predictions.
 We investigate what causes both instability in the likelihoods and under
 prediction during 10-fold cross-validation here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We looked at the difference in maximum likelihood estimates of biomass versus
 the difference in pollen compositions to assess where bimodality may occur
 (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:hexplots"

\end_inset

).
 We did this by computing the pairwise difference between the biomass maximum
 likelihood value and the difference in pollen composition using square
 cord distance (Eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chord dist"

\end_inset

) for all samples in the calibration and prediction datasets.
 As the difference in composition increases, the difference in the estimated
 biomass also increases in general in both the calibration and prediction
 datasets, but one can also see that for a given (often small) difference
 in composition there can be both large and small differences in estimated
 biomass.
 When viewing this relationship at individual sites (not shown), we see
 that some sites are more prone to instability, with small changes in compositio
n leading to large changes in predicted biomass.
 We identified these sites using the individual site plots of difference
 between compositions and difference between biomass maximum likelihoods
 and show them in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:maps-calib-pred-bimodal"

\end_inset

.
 Sites with bimodal likelihoods tend to have a large amount of oak pollen,
 small amounts of prairie pollen, and at some sites moderate amounts of
 beech pollen, indicating the model has a hard time predicting biomass in
 savanna-like conditions, particularly when late-successional arboreal pollen
 is present.
 
