\begin_layout Section
No Analog Assessment 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:No-analog-assessment"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No analog pollen compositions, a well known phenomena in paleo-ecology,
 are pollen compositions that have no modern analog.
 We need to be particularly careful of them because they are not represented
 in our calibration model and therefore it is difficult to make good biomass
 predictions for such samples.
 We assess all pollen count samples used in the prediction model for no
 analog communities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We look for no analog communities by measuring the square chord distance
 between samples.
 The chord distance between samples 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{jk}$
\end_inset

, is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{jk}=\sqrt{\sum_{k=1}^{K}\left(x_{ij}^{0.5}-x_{ik}^{0.5}\right)^{2}}\label{eq:chord dist}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the proportion of taxon 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in sample 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 We compute the distances using the R package 'analogue' version 0.17-0 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "simpson2013analogue"

\end_inset

.
 The vast majority of our prediction dataset samples had distance values
 of less than 0.2 relative to the calibration dataset (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:No-analog-figure"

\end_inset

).
 Standard paleo-ecological studies use a benchmark of 0.3 as a threshold
 for no-analog communities (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "flower1997matching"

\end_inset

).
 Furthermore, we computed the likelihood value evaluated at the maximum
 likelihood estimate of biomass for each of the samples and looked to see
 if these varied systematically with sample age.
 This gives us an idea if the data are less well-explained by the model
 further back in time.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:nax-liks-by-age"

\end_inset

 shows no pattern in the maximum likelihood values as a function of age,
 giving additional confidence that it is reasonable to estimate biomass
 throughout our 10000 year study period.
\end_layout

