\begin_layout Section
Exploring Different Taxon Groupings and Taxon-specific Predictive Power
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Exploring-Different-Taxa"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We computed the effects of different groupings of pollen by using the training
 and testing calibration datasets to assess predictive performance when
 grouping the pollen taxa into a variety of groups.
 These different groups were composed to explore ideas related to what plant
 traits can explain variations in biomass.
 First, we grouped our pollen taxa into the original leaf physiology-based
 plant functional type groups: grass (or prairie here), deciduous, and conifer.
 Second, we categorized pollen taxa into three trait categories based on
 a principal component analysis of seed mass, wood density, and leaf mass
 area between taxa.
 These are the dominant plant traits found to explain global vegetation
 distribution in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "van2014fully"

\end_inset

.
 Third, we organized pollen taxa into dominant biome types: forest, savanna,
 and prairie.
 Fourth, we divided pollen taxa into shade tolerance categories.
 We decided shade tolerance categories based on the dominant species shade
 tolerance classification in each genus.
 Finally, we used hemlock and beech pollen individually and aggregated all
 other pollen types into an 'other' category.
 We tested each validation fit for three things: linear 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

, mean squared error, and average variance for each point prediction to
 determine which grouping best reproduced settlement point estimates of
 above ground biomass.
 To avoid overfitting, similarly to the full model validation, we fit the
 validation plots using the training dataset and we report the values for
 both the training and testing dataset validations.
 These results are reported in the main manuscript text and figure 2, which
 shows the importance of successional status and in particular of hemlock
 and beech.
 
\end_layout

